  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Postface to the Collected Works of Geupam
  author: Lee In-bok
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Geupam Minister Min was my predecessor in learning. His grandson Gyeongji, passing by my home, spoke to me thus: "My ancestor possessed great virtue, yet went unrecognized—this is a failure of discernment. To know of it and fail to transmit it is a failure of benevolence. My grandfather's virtues and accomplishments are already well recorded in the national histories, requiring no effort of mine to preserve. But his poems—several hundred of them—possess equal beauty, and yet they remain unknown to the world. Who then shall bear responsibility for their loss? Thus I have gathered and published them, that their renown might spread. Master Ikjae wrote the first preface, and both Master Damam and Master Mokun followed with their own, moved by this young man's diligence and wishing that my grandfather's legacy not fade into obscurity. Yet you, who once walked with my grandfather—how can you alone remain silent on this matter?"

    Alas, what is poetry but the artistry of words? When speech flows from the heart and takes on form, how can we regard the poet's work as trivial? Geupam possessed a nature both pure and generous, and lived in an age of great flourishing. Having long cultivated his inner character, his poems attain a serene gentleness both lofty and refined. Those who read them perceive in them the mark of a true master, and it is no wonder that three worthy scholars have praised them so. Why then should my words be necessary for their transmission to posterity? Yet Gyeongji, showing me kindness despite my modest talents, has asked me to record the reasons for this collection. I dare not refuse, and so I set down these thoughts for those who come after.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Geupam (及菴) was the pen name of Minister Min, a respected elder scholar of the author's time.
  - key: ''
    value: The three worthy scholars mentioned—Master Ikjae (益齋), Master Damam (淡菴), and Master Mokun (牧隱)—were notable literati who each contributed prefaces to this collection.
